Assuming that your FetchXml is correct (it isn&#39;t) and that your `DataSet` object really is returning results as you claim in your question, the problem appears to be in your JavaScript where you loop through the results and display them in the HTML

You&#39;re expecting multiple results, but your HTML only has a single set of elements, and your success callback was only every getting the `starttime` property of the first result. You have to build your html dynamically based on the number of results you have.

HTML
----

- Remove all the span elements from your HTML - you need to build these dynamically
- Give your container `div` an id so you can find it in jquery

It should look something like this

    &lt;div id=&quot;meetingcollection&quot;&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;

Success Callback
----------------

You have a lot of problems in your javascript

- You have your conditional `if` inside your `for` loop. Check you have results before you start looping
- Your `for` loop is wrong - why do you have `subject` in your loop counter
- Declare the `i` variable in your `for` loop or it gets promoted to a global variable
- I don&#39;t know what `AP` is. I&#39;ve removed this variable and replaced it with dynamically building the html controls for each property (`starttime`,`location`,`regarding`,`whowith`)

In my example below, I&#39;m creating the controls with `document.createElement` but there are many ways you can do this


    var onSuccessfulExecution = function(results)
    {
      if (results != null &amp;&amp; results.value != null)              // check your &#39;results.value&#39; object - not sure why you were checking &#39;subject&#39;
      {
        var meetingFragment = document.createDocumentFragment(); // create a document fragment to hold all your elements
        for (var i=0; i &lt; results.value.length; i++)             // declare your &#39;i&#39; variable with var (or let)
        {
          var startSpan = document.createElement(&quot;span&quot;);        // create a span element for each field
          startSpan.className = &quot;start-time&quot;;                    // apply your class name
          startSpan.innerHTML = results.value[i].starttime;      // use the &#39;i&#39; variable to get the &#39;starttime&#39; for this result

          var locationSpan = document.createElement(&quot;span&quot;);     // repeat for each property
          locationSpan.className = &quot;location&quot;;
          locationSpan.innerHTML = results.value[i].location;

          // repeat for &#39;regarding&#39; and &#39;whowith&#39; properties

          meetingFragment.appendChild(startSpan);                // add the `span` objects to the fragment
          meetingFragment.appendChild(locationSpan);
        }

        var container = $(&quot;#meetingcollection&quot;);                 // your jquery selector must be wrapped in quotes - it is a string!
        container.appendChild(meetingFragment);                  // add the fragment to your html page
      }
    };

